<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-09-11T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-09-11T15:00:00-05:00" n="368" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d368">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00 R 29/336: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-09-11T21:00:00+01:00"><hi rend="italic">September
                                            11, 1920—9 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received September
                                    11—4:22 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>1685. B–242 for Davis, my B–238.<note n="86" xml:id="d368fn86"><hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_431">p.
                                    431</ref>.</note></p>
                            <p>Bradbury formula brought up rather unexpectedly to-day. Was accepted
                                by everyone after a specific explanation by Dubois and Bradbury that
                                all rights of powers not parties were reserved and arrangements of
                                agreement were applicable only to powers which signed. Result
                                entirely satisfactory. Dubois expressed to me his personal
                                gratification at result my proposed protest which protest of course
                                was not presented. Boyden.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wallace</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>